Split data into train and split sets

set.seed(123)
smp_size <- floor(0.75 * nrow(LifeExpData))
train_ind  <- sample(seq_len(nrow(LifeExpData)), size = smp_size)
LifeExpData <- LifeExpData[train_ind, ]
test <- LifeExpData[-train_ind, ]

Merge original dataset with country coordinates data. Then, convert coordinates to numeric. For latitude, make Southern values negative, and for longitude, make western values negative.

Geo = read.csv(file = "Countries_Long_Lat.csv")
LifeExpData <- merge(x = LifeExpData, y = Geo, by = "Country")

LifeExpData$Latitude <- ifelse(str_detect(LifeExpData$Latitude, "S"), paste("-", LifeExpData$Latitude, sep=""), LifeExpData$Latitude)
LifeExpData$Latitude = substr(LifeExpData$Latitude,1,nchar(LifeExpData$Latitude)-1)
LifeExpData$Latitude <- as.numeric(LifeExpData$Latitude)

LifeExpData$Longitude <- ifelse(str_detect(LifeExpData$Longitude, "W"), paste("-", LifeExpData$Longitude, sep=""), LifeExpData$Longitude)
LifeExpData$Longitude = substr(LifeExpData$Longitude,1,nchar(LifeExpData$Longitude)-1)
LifeExpData$Longitude <- as.numeric(LifeExpData$Longitude)

Visualize lat and long against life expectancy

ggplot(LifeExpData %>% distinct(Country, .keep_all = TRUE) , aes(y=Life.expectancy, x=Latitude)) + geom_point(alpha=0.5)
## Warning: Removed 7 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(LifeExpData %>% distinct(Country, .keep_all = TRUE), aes(y=Life.expectancy, x=Longitude)) + geom_point(alpha=0.5)

plot3d(

View correlations between quantitative variables

quant <- subset(LifeExpData, select=-c(Country, Status))
chart.Correlation(quant, histogram=FALSE, pch=19)

We can see our response variable, LifeExpectancy, has correlations up to .75. Predictor variables have correlations up to 1 with one-another. Lets view the scatterplots

We can see a few points of concern, such as some strong outliers. Additionally, some variables have distinct branches, such as Adult.Mortality. Lets explore these variables to see if we can determine the cause. First, we will color based off developed or undeveloped status.

plot(y = LifeExpData$Life.expectancy, x = LifeExpData$Adult.Mortality, col = LifeExpData$Status)

Counties frequently appear in both groups above. For example, Afghanistan has a 3 listed for Adult.Mortality in one year, and all the others years fall between 260 and 320. Similar situations occur with many other counties such as Armenia, South Sudan, and Spain. It seems clear the cause is a reporting error, in which countries incorrectly reported their statistic as per 100 population or per 10 population. It should be reported as per 1000 population.

Now, lets examine similar situations from above. First, infant.deaths:

India should have a population above 1 billion each year, but is often in the tens/hundreds of millions in the dataset. China should have very large populations as well, but they range from 13,000 to 1.4 million. These should be about 1.4 billion. In addition, some major countries like the U.S. are missing all of its population data.
